        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                  Use tables to find the reciprocal of <m>0.154</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
           Given <m>0.154</m>, first write it in standard form: <m>1.54 \times 10^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
        <image source="reciprocal2.png">
            <shortdescription>extract of mathematical table</shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
            Then, to locate the reciprocal of the given number:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                      Move down the column headed <m>x</m> to locate <m>1.5</m>.  
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       Move to the right along the row that has <m>1.5</m> to the column headed <m>4</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       Read the number at the intersection of the row and column which is <m>0.6494</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>                   
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
           Calculate the reciprocal of <m>10^{-1}</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
           Since <m>10^{-1}</m> can be written as <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> then its reciprocal is <m>\frac{10}{1} = 10</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Multiply <m>0.6494</m> by <m>10</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The reciprocal of <m>0.154</m> is <m>6.494</m>
        </p>
    </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Murunga's car consumes <m>\frac{1}{8}</m> liters of fuel per kilometer. Use tables to identify how far Murunga can drive with 1 liter?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    If <m>\frac{1}{8} \text{l} =1</m>km, 
                      Then <m> 1 \text{l}= ?</m> km
                </p>
                <p>
                  To find the distance Murunga drove using <m>1</m> l, we first convert <m>\frac{1}{8}</m> to a decimal i.e <m>1\div8 = 0.125</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next, we write <m>0.125</m> in standard form: <m>1.25 \times 10^{-1}</m>.
                </p>
                <image source="reciprocal2.png">
                    <shortdescription>extract of mathematical table</shortdescription>
                </image>
                <p>
                   Move down the column headed <m>x</m> to locate <m>1.2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Move to the right along the row that has <m>1.2</m> to the column headed <m>5</m>.   
                </p>
                <p>
                   Read the number at the intersection of the row and column which is <m>0.8000</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Calculate the reciprocal of <m>10^{-1}</m>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Since <m>10^{-1}</m> can be written as <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> then its reciprocal is <m>\frac{10}{1} = 10</m>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Multiply <m>0.8000</m> by <m>10</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                   <m>0.8000 \times 10 = 8</m>  
                </p>
                <p>
                   Therefore, Murunga can drive <m>8</m> km using <m>1</m> l of fuel.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
